<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>

<head>
<title>@HI{{to}}</title>
<link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="japanese.css"/>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8">
</head>

<body>

<h1>@HI{{to}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @N{{}} <strong>@HI{{to}}</strong> ... 
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<a name="list"><strong>@HI{{to}}</strong></a> follows nouns to indicate "and".
It can only be used with nouns and not phrases or clauses.
In this usage <strong>@HI{{to}}</strong> follows each noun except the last.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{white}}iyuri<strong>to</strong>@KJ{{red}}ibarano@KJ{{flower}}wo@KJ{{buy}}imashou.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Let's buy some white lillies and red roses.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{to}}</strong> can be used to mark a comparison or contrast.
sentence.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{ringo}}<strong>to</strong>mikann<strong>to</strong>dochiraga@KJ{{fond}}kidesuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Which do you like better, apples or mandarin oranges.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<a name="with"><strong>@HI{{to}}</strong></a> can mean "with" to indicate participants in an action.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{company^long}}ha @KJ{{section^long}}<strong>to</strong>@KJ{{eat^matter}}woshiteimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The company president is eating out with the division manager.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{to}}</strong> can indicate a change or a result.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{now^year}}ni@KJ{{sea^outside^trip^going^someone}}ha 1000@KJ{{ten*thousand^person}}<strong>to</strong>natta.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      This year the number of overseas travellers reached ten million.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
Following an expression of quantity, <strong>@HI{{to}}</strong> reinforces the negative idea of the sentence.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ano@KJ{{mountain}}ni@KJ{{ascend}}runiha, 2@KJ{{time^interval}}<strong>to</strong>kakarimasenn.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      It won't even take two hours to climb that mountain.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<a name="quote"><strong>@HI{{to}}</strong></a> can indicate what someone says, asks or orders or <a href="grammar-to-omou.html">thinks</a>.
In this usage it acts as a quotation marker.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{mountain^book}}sanga, atode@KJ{{electricity^tale}}suru<strong>to</strong>osshaimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Yamamoto said that she would phone later.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
In the form <a href="grammar-to-iu.html"><strong>@HI{{to}}</strong>@HI{{iu}}</a> it indicates the name of something
about which an explanation follows.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{come^year}}ha,@KT{{amerika}}he@KJ{{going}}kou<strong>to</strong>@KJ{{consider}}eteimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I'm thinking of going to the US next year.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{to}}</strong> indicates the name of something, about which an explanation follows.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{generation^world}}<strong>to</strong>iu@KJ{{miscellaneous^document}}wo@KJ{{know}}tteimasuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Do you know the magazine called <em>Sekai</em>?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{to}}</strong> follows an onomatopoeic verb.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{star}}gakirakira<strong>to</strong>@KJ{{radiance}}iteimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The stars are twinkling.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{to}}</strong> indicates that a second action immediately follows a preceding one. In this usage, 
@HI{{sugu}} is often present too.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{morning^rouse}}kiru<strong>to</strong>sugu, @KT{{ka-tenn}}wo@KJ{{open}}kemasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      As soon as I get up in the morning, I open the curtains.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<a name="condition"><strong>@HI{{to}}</strong></a> can indicate the inevitability of a second action.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{car}}ga@KJ{{many}}kunaru<strong>to</strong>@KJ{{mingle^traffic^thing^happenstance}}ga@KJ{{increase}}masu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      As the number of cars increases, more traffic accidents occur.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{to}}</strong> can indicate a hypothetical condition.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{bright^day}},@KJ{{heavens^spirit}}gaii<strong>to</strong>@KJ{{plains^ball}}gadekimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      If the weather is good tomorrow we can play baseball.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{to}}</strong> can indicate that something has been learned as a result of an action.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{mingle^turn}}de@KJ{{road-way}}wokiku<strong>to</strong>,sono@KJ{{meeting^company}}hasugu@KJ{{see}}tsukatta.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      After asking the way at a police box, I found the company straightaway.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{to}}</strong> follows two verbs in the volitional, or the same verb firstly in the volitional and secondly in @HI{{mai}},
to indicate a lack of concern over which of two events occurs.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{he^woman}}ga@KJ{{one^person}}de@KT{{pa-texi-}}ni@KJ{{going}}kou<strong>to</strong>,
      @KJ{{going}}kumai<strong>to</strong>, @KJ{{private}}hakamaimasenn.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I don't care whether she goes to the party alone or not.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
When <strong>@HI{{to}}</strong> follows a noun + @HI{{ga}} or noun + @HI{{wo}}, <strong>@HI{{to}}</strong>
replaces those particles. For all other particles, <strong>@HI{{to}}</strong> follows them rather than
replacing them.
</p>

